Responsive UI testing examined layout behavior across device emulation presets, verifying that images maintained aspect ratios without distortion, that text remained readable without horizontal scrolling at minimum widths (320px), and that navigation elements reflowed appropriately without overlapping content. Visual regression testing compared initial mockups against final implementations to identify deviations from approved designs.

### 6.4 Browser Compatibility Testing
Cross-browser validation ensured consistent user experiences across diverse client environments. Testing matrices included Google Chrome (versions 115+), Mozilla Firefox (versions 115+), Microsoft Edge (versions 115+), and Apple Safari (versions 16+). Venkateshwaran executed systematic testing protocols on each platform, documenting rendering differences, JavaScript console errors, and CSS layout discrepancies.

Chrome testing served as the baseline given its Blink rendering engine and comprehensive developer tool availability. Firefox testing identified potential flexbox interpretation differences and verified that CSS Grid implementations degraded gracefully where utilized. Edge testing confirmed Chromium-based consistency while validating Windows-specific font rendering. Safari testing (conducted on macOS and iOS devices) addressed WebKit-specific behaviors including flexbox gap support, image rendering, and form element styling peculiarities.

Legacy browser testing examined functionality on Internet Explorer 11 where feasible, implementing graceful degradation strategies when full support proved impossible given modern CSS utilization. Mobile browser testing extended to Chrome Mobile, Safari iOS, and Samsung Internet to ensure touch-specific behaviors functioned correctly across mobile operating systems.

### 6.5 Bug Fixing
Testing phases identified various technical deficiencies requiring systematic resolution. Navigation bugs included incorrect relative path references (./index.html vs /index.html) causing failures when pages were accessed from subdirectories, corrected through absolute path standardization or consistent relative path implementation. CSS specificity conflicts between custom styles and Bootstrap defaults required !important declarations or selector specificity adjustments to achieve intended visual results.

JavaScript debugging addressed form validation edge cases including special character handling in name fields and international telephone number format variations. Console error elimination resolved undefined variable references and deprecated method usage (particularly regarding Bootstrap 5's abandonment of jQuery dependencies). Image loading failures traced to case sensitivity discrepancies between filename references and actual file storage (contact.jpg vs Contact.jpg) were rectified through systematic filename standardization.

Responsive layout bugs included container overflow issues on tablet viewports (768px-992px range), addressed through Bootstrap column class adjustments (col-sm-6 vs col-md-4). Z-index stacking context errors affecting mobile navigation overlays required explicit z-index declarations and positioning context establishment.

### 6.6 Validation
