Resolution involved implementing color management workflows using ICC profiles, creating physical proofing sessions during on-site weeks to compare printed packaging samples against calibrated monitor displays, and establishing acceptable variance tolerances for color matching between media. Standardized asset export protocols ensured that web-optimized images of packaging maintained visual consistency with physical products.

### 7.7 Limited Internship Duration
The six-week temporal constraint imposed significant pressure on deliverable quality and comprehensiveness. Challenges included insufficient time for extensive user research, compressed testing phases, and limited opportunity for iterative design refinement based on extended user feedback. The hybrid schedule, while offering flexibility, reduced collaborative face-time essential for complex problem-solving during integration phases.

Resolution required strict adherence to agile methodologies with one-week sprints, prioritization of core functional requirements over nice-to-have features, and early client consultation to validate directional decisions before extensive development investment. Timeboxing design phases ensured that packaging work concluded by Week 3, allowing Weeks 4-6 to focus exclusively on website integration, testing, and deployment.

### 7.8 Testing All Webpages Before Deployment
Comprehensive quality assurance within constrained timeframes presented resource allocation challenges. Manual testing of seven pages across multiple browsers, devices, and viewport sizes generated extensive test matrices requiring significant temporal investment. Venkateshwaran faced difficulty balancing thorough testing protocols with integration responsibilities, particularly regarding edge case identification (unusual form inputs, slow network conditions, accessibility screen reader compatibility).

Resolution implemented risk-based testing prioritization, focusing intensive testing efforts on critical user paths (Home → Products → Contact) while utilizing automated tools for baseline HTML/CSS validation. Checklist-based testing protocols ensured consistent coverage across pages without redundant effort, while peer review processes distributed testing responsibilities among team members.

### 7.9 Managing Client Feedback
Stakeholder management presented challenges regarding scope creep, subjective aesthetic preferences, and technical limitation communications. Client requests occasionally conflicted with minimalism requirements or technical feasibility within the static site constraints. Venkateshwaran encountered situations where feedback on packaging designs required extensive revision late in the production timeline, threatening website integration schedules.

Resolution established formal feedback protocols with structured review sessions at Week 2 (mockups) and Week 4 (final integration), documented change request procedures, and clear communication regarding technical constraints (no animations, static site limitations). Prototype presentations using InVision or similar tools allowed client visualization before coding investment, reducing late-stage revision requirements.

